node.text: Videos showing people smuggling migrants past Border Patrol checkpoints and flashing thousands of dollars in cash are being posted on TikTok, Texas State Troopers say. This is a new and dangerous tactic to recruit teens to drive migrants from the US-Mexico border to Houston and other Texas cities — with one video offering $4,500 per person they smuggle. CNN's @rosaflorescnn reports.

node.title: Mexican cartels are recruiting teens on TikTok to smuggle migrants

node.text: Fifty-three years ago, a government commission investigated civil unrest and racial inequality in America. The results from the "Kerner Report" shocked the country but mostly faded into history. The last surviving member, 90-year-old Fred Harris, shares why.

node.text: The April 12 police killing Anthony Thompson Jr. inside of a bathroom at Knoxville's Austin-East Magnet High School has sparked a wave of protests throughout the city. Thompson is the school's fifth student to die at the hands of gun violence this year, and many in the Black community say they've reached a boiling point. We went to the frontlines of demonstrations to speak with activists, teachers, and residents who say they're committed to calling attention to systemic failures plaguing the Black community in Knoxville.

node.text:
Sohail Pardis was one of the thousands of Afghan interpreters who worked for the US military. The Taliban shot at his car, dragged him out and beheaded him, according to villagers who witnessed the incident. Now, other interpreters fear persecution as the Taliban gains control of wider swaths of the country.⁠
⁠
(📸: Family Handout)

node.text: During the CNN town hall Wednesday night, President Biden made a number of false and misleading claims, including saying you’re not going to get Covid if you’re vaccinated. Biden’s blanket promises — that vaccinated people are simply “not going to be hospitalized,” “not going to die” and, even with the very contagious Delta variant, “not going to get Covid” — were inaccurate.

node.text:
Ugandan Annet Negesa and Kenyan Maximila Imali both had their Olympic dreams crushed because of rules set by track and field global governing body World Athletics. They are just two – of many – elite women athletes who have been told their natural testosterone levels, if not lowered through medication or surgery, disqualify them from competition at the highest levels of sport. 

Tap the link in our bio for CNN's full report.

Intersex people have natural variations in reproductive anatomy, chromosome patterns or other traits that may not align with typical binary definitions of female or male. These variations are sometimes called differences in sex development, or DSD. It is difficult to estimate how many people have DSD traits many live their entire lives without ever knowing they have one. Scientists estimate as many as one out of every 50 people is born with DSD traits. CNN RUNNING AS EQUALS'.

Photo by CNN on July 22, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Does testosterone affect athletic performance? "There is good evidence to show muscle bulk increases with increasing dosage of testosterone," said retired endocrinologist Peter Sonksen. But he said the relationship between blood testosterone level and performance remains "complex and controversial." "[World Athletics] are trying to refine further and further as the policies come under scrutiny. But the science is still very much contested," said author and anthropologist Katrina Karkazis. Karkazis told CNN that the lack of conclusive evidence hasn't stopped World Athletics from forming its policies. CNN RUNNING AS EQUALS'.
